List/array dependencies

When several registrations of IService exist in a container, many frameworks automatically provide IService[] (or List etc).

This is extremely important for open/closed principle. For example, UserValidator can have dependency on IUserValidationRule[]. Then new rules can be transparently added to the system without any changes to UserValidator.

@dotnetjunkie: .NET 4.5 introduced two new collection interfaces IReadOnlyCollection and IReadOnlyList that define 'finite iterator' behavior and DI frameworks should natively support these interface to prevent defensive copying of arrays (as Mark Seemann explains here http://blog.ploeh.dk/2013/07/20/linq-versus-the-lsp/).

Framework IService[] IList<IService> ICollection<IService> IEnumerable<IService> IReadOnlyCollection<IService> IReadOnlyList<IService>

  1. Simple Injector does support resolving IEnumerable, but requires a single registration using one of the RegisterAll methods to register all types at once, which is a different strategy than the other frameworks use.

  2. Note: Unity requires named registrations for list resolution to work.

Generics support

Open generic registration

Allows registration of open generic types.
For example, Service<> can be registered as IService<>, and then any request for IService should be resolved with Service.

Constraint support for open generics

For open generic registration, library does not use Service to resolve request for IService if X does not match generic constraints on T.

Framework Open generic registration Constraint support for open generics
Autofac supported supported
Castle supported supported
Catel failed see comment1
Dynamo.Ioc failed see comment1
LinFu supported failed
Ninject supported failed
Simple Injector supported see comment2
Spring.NET failed see comment1
StructureMap supported supported
Unity supported see comment3

  1. Skipped as Open generic registration (Generics support) is not supported by this framework.

  2. Simple Injector does support filtering based on generic type constraints, but in case of registering a collection of open generic types, it only allows all elements to be registered at once. Open generic collections can be registered using RegisterAllOpenGeneric. See: http://bit.ly/14DQx7c.

  3. Skipped as IEnumerable (List/array dependencies) is not supported by this framework.

Automatic factories (Func<TService>)

When TService is registered in a container, many frameworks automatically provide Func<..., TService>.

This is very useful for mixing lifetimes: for example, singleton (Service) may have a Func dependency on transient (DataContext), which allows it to get/dispose a new instance of transient when it is needed.

No parameters

Registration of TService automatically provides Func.

Parameter for dependency

Registration of TService automatically provides Func<..., TService>, where any arguments to the factory define constructor parameter overrides.

For example, registration Service(IService1, IService2) can provide Func or Func or Func. Remaining parameters are provided by the container.

Singleton using transient

When TService is transient and Func was obtained by singleton, Func should return new instance on each call.

Property dependencies

While property dependencies are a nice feature, it is rarely a good practice to actually use them.

I have not yet decided whether this table is worth keeping, so do not assign much weight to these tests.

Dependency without attributes

Normally, it is undesirable to reference DI framework from the most parts of the code.
Requirement to use explicit attributes contributes to this problem.

Convenience

Features that simplify development and reduce surprises.

Best constructor selection

If multiple constructors are present, DI framework should select the one that developer would have selected, having the same services.

In this situation, it seems reasonable to select constructor with most resolvable dependencies.

Graceful recursion handling

Recursive dependencies are non-resolvable, however the difference between getting a StackOverflowException and any other one is significant.

StackOverflowException will crash the whole process, which is really undesirable, even if it is only an integration test environment. Debugging such issue can be a huge annoyance.

  2. Simple Injector does not allow resolving types with multiple constructors out of the box, but this behavior can be changed by replacing the Container.Options.ConstructorResolutionBehavior. For more info see: https://bit.ly/13WKdRT.
